B2(a) — Data Joining and Grain 
The data comes from four tables: transactions, store attributes, promotion details, and calendar.
First, I would join the tables using common keys:
Join transactions with store attributes using store_id
Join transactions with promotion details using promotion_type
Join transactions with calendar using transaction_date
After joining, all information will be in one dataset.
Grain of dataset:
One row represents one store on one date (or one transaction period).
Before modelling, I would perform some aggregations, such as:
Total items_sold per store per day/month
Average footfall
Count of promotions used
Possibly group data monthly if needed
This ensures the dataset is consistent and suitable for modelling.


B2(b) — EDA Strategy 
Before building the model, I would perform the following analysis:
1. Distribution of items_sold
Plot: Histogram
Check: Is data skewed or normal?
Use: If highly skewed → may apply log transformation
2. Sales by promotion type
Plot: Bar chart
Check: Which promotions perform better
Use: Helps understand importance of promotion_type
3. Sales over time
Plot: Line chart (items_sold vs date/month)
Check: Trends, seasonality, festival spikes
Use: Confirms need for time-based features (month, weekend, festival)
4. Relationship between numerical features and sales
Plot: Scatter plots (e.g., footfall vs items_sold)
Check: Correlation or patterns
Use: Helps decide important features for model
5. Correlation heatmap (optional but useful)
Check: Strong relationships between variables
Use: Helps in feature selection


B2(c) — Imbalance Issue (2 marks)
Since 80% of transactions have no promotion, the data is imbalanced.
Problem:
Model may learn mostly from “no promotion” cases
It may not properly learn the effect of different promotions
Solution:
Ensure enough representation of promotion data
Use techniques like:
Sampling (oversample promotion cases or undersample non-promotion)
Add features to clearly capture promotion impact
Evaluate model separately on promotion vs non-promotion cases
